  "prompt": "How much do astrophysicists make at NASA?",
  "response": "The salary of astrophysicists at NASA can vary widely depending on factors such as experience, education, location, and specific job role. As of recent data, here\u2019s a general breakdown:\n\n1. **Entry-Level Positions**:  \n   - Astrophysicists just starting their careers (e.g., recent Ph.D. graduates) typically earn between **$60,000 and $90,000** per year.\n\n2. **Mid-Level Positions**:  \n   - With several years of experience, astrophysicists at NASA can earn between **$90,000 and $120,000** annually.\n\n3. **Senior-Level Positions**:  \n   - Highly experienced astrophysicists or those in leadership roles can earn **$120,000 to $160,000** or more per year.\n\n4. **Exceptionally High-Level Roles**:  \n   - For top-tier scientists, project leads, or directors, salaries can exceed **$160,000** annually.\n\n### Additional Considerations:\n- **Location**: Salaries may vary depending on the NASA center\u2019s location (e.g., higher costs of living in California or Washington, D.C., may result in higher pay).\n- **Education**: A Ph.D. is typically required for astrophysics roles, and advanced degrees can lead to higher compensation.\n- **Federal Pay Scales**: Many NASA employees are paid according to the **General Schedule (GS)** pay scale, which ranges from GS-11 to GS-15 for most scientific roles. Astrophysicists often fall into the GS-12 to GS-15 range, with salaries adjusted for locality.\n\nFor the most accurate and up-to-date information, you can refer to the **U.S. Office of Personnel Management (OPM)** website or NASA\u2019s official job postings.",
